1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,070
As a first example,

2

00:00:02,070  -->  00:00:06,450
let's apply this new idea of notation to something you've used before.

3

00:00:06,450  -->  00:00:11,835
Spreadsheets. Spreadsheets are a common way we hold data in the real world.

4

00:00:11,835  -->  00:00:15,824
In our spreadsheet, we have rows and columns.

5

00:00:15,824  -->  00:00:19,775
To better understand how we use spreadsheets to hold data,

6

00:00:19,775  -->  00:00:21,779
let's work through an example.

7

00:00:21,779  -->  00:00:23,945
Before even collecting data,

8

00:00:23,945  -->  00:00:27,570
we usually start with a question or many questions.

9

00:00:27,570  -->  00:00:29,820
Consider I run a small blog about my

10

00:00:29,820  -->  00:00:33,585
best and worst adventures with the dogs at the coffee shop.

11

00:00:33,585  -->  00:00:37,400
Which also sells trinkets related to those adventures.

12

00:00:37,400  -->  00:00:40,050
Everything from fetch toys to leashes,

13

00:00:40,050  -->  00:00:43,140
to doggie bags, and everything in between.

14

00:00:43,140  -->  00:00:47,265
Questions I might have are: How many people visit my site?

15

00:00:47,265  -->  00:00:50,504
Or how much time do visitors spend on my site?

16

00:00:50,504  -->  00:00:52,285
Are there differences in traffic,

17

00:00:52,285  -->  00:00:54,281
depending on the day of the week?

18

00:00:54,281  -->  00:00:57,975
How many visitors purchase an item through the blog?

19

00:00:57,975  -->  00:01:00,644
In order to answer these questions,

20

00:01:00,644  -->  00:01:03,450
say we keep track of the date of the visit,

21

00:01:03,450  -->  00:01:05,485
the day of the week of the visit,

22

00:01:05,485  -->  00:01:07,275
the amount of time spent on the site,

23

00:01:07,275  -->  00:01:10,259
and whether or not an individual buys an item.

24

00:01:10,259  -->  00:01:13,345
We can think of each of these as a column.

25

00:01:13,345  -->  00:01:17,795
A column in our dataset is associated with a random variable.

26

00:01:17,795  -->  00:01:22,180
Explaining what a random variable is in English is complicated.

27

00:01:22,180  -->  00:01:24,695
But in notation, it's simple.

28

00:01:24,695  -->  00:01:31,829
In English, a random variable is a placeholder for the possible values of some process.

29

00:01:31,829  -->  00:01:34,615
In notation, it's X.

30

00:01:34,615  -->  00:01:37,575
For our website, the date of the visit,

31

00:01:37,575  -->  00:01:39,730
the day of the week of the visit,

32

00:01:39,730  -->  00:01:41,715
the amount of time spent on the site,

33

00:01:41,715  -->  00:01:46,825
and whether or not an individual buys an item are all variables.

34

00:01:46,825  -->  00:01:50,760
Let's say we have a visitor on Thursday, June 15.

35

00:01:50,760  -->  00:01:56,130
The visitor stays on our site for five minutes and doesn't buy an item.

36

00:01:56,130  -->  00:01:57,375
Then a second visitor,

37

00:01:57,375  -->  00:02:03,659
visits the site on the exact same day for 10 minutes and they do buy an item.

38

00:02:03,659  -->  00:02:08,400
Notice how each of these individuals has been added to our spreadsheet.

39

00:02:08,400  -->  00:02:10,485
We might have many more visitors,

40

00:02:10,485  -->  00:02:13,565
and we could update our spreadsheet accordingly.

41

00:02:13,565  -->  00:02:16,220
When using spreadsheets, we frequently

42

00:02:16,220  -->  00:02:20,105
analyze a full column to answer our questions of interest.

43

00:02:20,105  -->  00:02:25,710
For example, to answer the question of how much time do visitors spend on our site?

44

00:02:25,710  -->  00:02:28,100
We need to look at this column.

45

00:02:28,100  -->  00:02:29,570
To answer the question of,

46

00:02:29,570  -->  00:02:31,365
Are there differences in traffic,

47

00:02:31,365  -->  00:02:33,100
depending on the day of the week?

48

00:02:33,100  -->  00:02:35,125
We need to look at this column.

49

00:02:35,125  -->  00:02:37,075
And to answer the question of,

50

00:02:37,075  -->  00:02:39,635
How many purchases occur through our blog?

51

00:02:39,635  -->  00:02:41,685
We need to look at this column.

52

00:02:41,685  -->  00:02:49,395
Mathematically, we usually consider a random variable or column using a capital letter.

53

00:02:49,395  -->  00:02:52,115
Commonly, we use the capital letter X,

54

00:02:52,115  -->  00:02:54,950
but we can just as easily use Y,

55

00:02:54,950  -->  00:02:58,135
Z or any other capital letter.

56

00:02:58,135  -->  00:03:01,415
We might say, consider the random variable X,

57

00:03:01,415  -->  00:03:05,655
which signifies the amount of time an individual spends on our website.

58

00:03:05,655  -->  00:03:09,680
Therefore, X relates to this entire column.

59

00:03:09,680  -->  00:03:11,990
Consider we also have a random variable Y,

60

00:03:11,990  -->  00:03:16,380
which signifies whether or not an individual purchases an item from the website,

61

00:03:16,380  -->  00:03:20,250
so Y relates to this entire column.
